Introduction

This is a case study where I work as an junior data analyst in the marketing analyst team at a imaginary company called Cyclistic. I was assigned the problem of how annual members use Cyclistic bikes differently to casual bikers. To clarify, a casual bikers are someone who purchase single-ride or full-day pass whereas annual members purchased a subscription for a year. Through these insights, I can make recommendations to the executive team regarding how to convert casual riders to annual riders. Because this is an imaginary company, the dat aset I will be using is a public data set that explores how different customers uses bikes. This data set is made available by Motivate International Inc. under this license. ## Setting up the environment

Data Visualization

Here, we will see a series of visualization on the differences of member and casual bikers

Ride length of Member vs. Casual

#this gets a graph of member and casual riders ride length
ride_length_2021_02 <- ggplot(data = trip_data_2021_02) +
  geom_histogram(mapping = aes(y = ride_length_rounded, fill = member_casual), stat = "count") +
  facet_wrap(~member_casual) +
  labs(title = "Ride length (2021 02)", subtitle = "Organized in a interval of 30 minutes", x = "number of bikers", y = "ride length") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, size=12),
        plot.subtitle = element_text(hjust = 0.5, size=9), 
        legend.title = element_blank(), 
        axis.ticks.y = element_blank(), 
        axis.text.y = element_blank(),
        axis.text.x = element_text(size = 8))

This graph shows that around half of proportion of casual bikers tend to ride around 30 minutes, whereas around half of proportion of member bikers tend to ride less than 30 minutes.

Distribution of days in a week used by Member vs. Casual

Setting up the graphs

#gets the distribution of days for the members
member_graph_dow_2021_02 <- member_dow_2021_02 %>% 
  group_by(day_of_week) %>% 
  summarize(count = n()) %>% 
  mutate(percent = count/sum(count)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = day_of_week, y = count, fill = day_of_week)) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity") +
  geom_text(aes(label = paste0(round(100*percent, 1), "%")), vjust = -0.25, size = 2.5) + 
  labs(title = "Member biker day distribution", subtitle = "Note: 1 = Sunday, 2 = Monday, etc") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5), plot.subtitle = element_text(hjust = 0.5))
